# Engineering Principles

## Before Changing Code

1. Read surrounding code and understand existing patterns
2. Reuse existing abstractions before introducing new ones
3. Extend existing files where reasonable; split only when separation genuinely helps
4. Do not modify unrelated files during a task
5. Preserve behavior during refactors unless behavior changes are explicitly requested

## Code Quality

- Prefer simple, readable code over clever abstractions
- Do not over-engineer
- Add comments only for non-obvious business logic
- Keep components focused and reasonably small
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Keep state local unless it genuinely needs to be shared
- Avoid unnecessary `useEffect` and unnecessary derived state

## Typing

The codebase is JavaScript (`.js`/`.jsx`). Use JSDoc types on non-trivial functions. Do not migrate to TypeScript or add `.ts` files unless explicitly requested.

## Dependencies & Tests

- Do not install new npm dependencies without asking first
- Write tests when modifying critical business logic (`ratingEngine.js`, `useGameLogger.js`) or when specifically requested
- No test infrastructure exists yet — discuss approach before adding one

## Priorities

Business logic and product outcomes matter more than technical elegance. Prefer solutions that make the product easier to evolve.

Optimize for shipping speed while maintaining clean, maintainable code.

## Sensitive Areas

- `utils/ratingEngine.js` — canonical rating math; change with care
- `hooks/useGameLogger.js` — canonical match write path
- `Dashboard.jsx` — large god component; do not refactor unless asked
- Auth uses custom PIN + `bcryptjs` in browser, not Supabase Auth
